    overtakingDifficulty:
      "Low to Moderate — three DRS zones along the circuit's long straights compensate for the reduced aerodynamic grip that altitude creates, and the altitude paradoxically produces higher top speeds than almost any other circuit because the thin air reduces drag as effectively as it reduces downforce. Turn 1 remains the primary overtaking zone, and the approach to it from the main straight is one of the most dramatic braking zones on the calendar.",
    famousFor:
      "Mexico City is famous for the Foro Sol baseball stadium section — a 30,000-seat venue that the circuit passes directly through, with fans packed into its stands just metres from the passing cars, creating a wall of colour and sound that is uniquely intense even by Formula 1 standards. Since Sergio Pérez joined Red Bull Racing in 2021, his home Grand Prix has become one of the most commercially and emotionally charged events on the calendar — tickets sell out within hours, and the Mexican crowd's passion for their national hero creates an atmosphere that rivals Silverstone and Zandvoort for raw intensity.",
    history:
      "The Autodromo Hermanos Rodriguez opened in 1959 and first hosted a Formula 1 World Championship race in 1963. The circuit carries the names of brothers Ricardo and Pedro Rodríguez — Ricardo died here in a non-championship qualifying session in 1962 at just 20 years old, in one of the most tragic events in the circuit's early history. The Mexican Grand Prix appeared on the calendar through 1970, returned in 1986, and ran until 1992 before financial difficulties again led to its departure. The modern era of the Mexican Grand Prix began with a redesigned circuit and the spectacular stadium section in 2015, and it has been a permanent calendar fixture since.",
